 ---
  sshmngr — Full Feature Specification

  Overview

  A terminal SSH connection manager. Shows a list of known hosts in a TUI, lets the user pick one via
  fuzzy autocomplete, and launches ssh as a subprocess with the correct arguments.

  ---
  CLI Interface

  - sshmngr — launch interactive TUI
  - sshmngr <hostname> — connect directly (skip TUI prompt, still resolves host)
  - sshmngr --list-hosts — print all hostnames one per line (used by shell tab completion)

  ---
  Configuration (config.ini)

  Search order: ./config.ini (CWD) first, then ~/.config/sshmngr/config.ini (or
  $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/sshmngr/).

  Format quirk: The file has no [section] header. Before parsing, inject [main] at the top.

  Keys:

  ┌─────────────────┬───────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │       Key       │     Type      │                 Description                  │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ global_jumphost │ bool (yes/no) │ Whether to use the jump server for all hosts │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ jumpserver      │ string        │ Hostname/IP of the jump server               │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ jumpuser        │ string        │ Username for the jump server                 │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ ssh_user        │ string        │ Default SSH user for all connections         │
  └─────────────────┴───────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  ---
  Host List (hosts.csv)

  Search order: Same as config.ini — CWD first, then ~/.config/sshmngr/.

  Format auto-detection (by inspecting CSV header, case-insensitive):

  ┌──────────────┬────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │   Header     │     Format     │                          Columns used                          │
  │   contains   │                │                                                                │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ hostname     │ Full format    │ hostname, host, port, user, jumphost, jumpuser, notes, legacy  │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ name + ip    │ XIQ-SE export  │ name→hostname, ip address→host; optional: port, user,          │
  │ address      │                │ jumphost, jumpuser, notes, legacy; extra columns ignored       │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ host + addr  │ Two-column     │ host→hostname, addr→IP                                         │
  │              │ shorthand      │                                                                │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Any other    │ Generic CSV    │ col[0]→hostname, col[1]→IP                                     │
  │ header       │                │                                                                │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ No header    │ Raw list       │ col[0]→hostname (one per line)                                 │
  └──────────────┴────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  HostEntry fields:
  - hostname — display name / alias
  - host — IP or FQDN to connect to (can be empty; falls back to hostname)
  - port — integer, default 22
  - user — per-host username override
  - jumphost — per-host jump server override
  - jumpuser — per-host jump user override
  - notes — free text shown in the table
  - legacy — bool; enables ssh-rsa compat for this host (set via legacy=yes in CSV)

  Lines starting with # are skipped. Entries are sorted alphabetically by hostname (case-insensitive).

  ---
  TUI Display

  When rich is available:
  1. ASCII wizard art banner (11 lines, colored cyan/yellow)
  2. Header line: sshmngr  v{VERSION}  ·  Jump: user@server  ·  User: username
  3. Horizontal rule
  4. Host table with columns: Hostname | IP / Host | Port | User | Via Jump | Notes
    - Port column is blank when port == 22
    - User shows effective user (per-host or global fallback)
    - Via Jump shows effective jump host (per-host or global if global_jumphost=yes)
  5. Hint line: Tab / type to autocomplete  ·  Enter to connect  ·  Ctrl+C to quit
  6. Slash-command hint: /o direct  ·  /v verbose  ·  /d dry-run  ·  /l legacy  (stackable)
  7. If scrolling active: ↑ ↓ to scroll  [start–end of total]

  Without rich: plain text fallback (version, jump/user info, then one host per line).

  ---
  Scrollable Host List

  When the host count exceeds what fits on screen:
  - Visible rows = max(3, terminal_height - 23) (23 = banner + chrome overhead)
  - Only the current slice is passed to the display function
  - ↑/↓ arrow keys adjust the scroll offset and redraw the screen
  - Scroll indicator shows current range: [1–20 of 47]
  - Scroll bindings are only registered when both rich and prompt_toolkit are available

  ---
  Interactive Prompt

  When prompt_toolkit is available:
  - Fuzzy word autocomplete on all known hostnames, active while typing
  - Auto-suggest from history (ghost text)
  - Persistent history stored in ~/.config/sshmngr/.history
  - Prompt is >  in bold cyan; turns bold orange and shows active flags when a slash command is active
  - Ctrl+C / EOF exits with code 130

  Slash command activation (WoW-style):
  Type a prefix (/o, /v, /d, /l) then press Space. The prefix is consumed from the buffer, the prompt
  label updates to show active flags, and the user continues typing the hostname normally. Multiple
  flags stack: /o then /v activates both. Flags reset after each connection.

  Also supports typed slash prefixes in the input (e.g. /o/v hostname) parsed directly.

  Without prompt_toolkit: plain input() fallback, supports typed slash prefixes only.

  ---
  Slash Commands

  ┌─────────┬─────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Command │      Flag       │                              SSH effect                              │
  ├─────────┼─────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ /o      │ bypass_jumphost │ Skip all jump logic; connect directly                                │
  ├─────────┼─────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ /v      │ verbose         │ Add -v to the ssh command                                            │
  ├─────────┼─────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ /d      │ dry_run         │ Print the ssh command, do not connect                                │
  ├─────────┼─────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ /l      │ legacy          │ Add -o HostKeyAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa -o                                 │
  │         │                 │ PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa                                    │
  └─────────┴─────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Stackable in any combination.

  ---
  Host Resolution (find_entry)

  Given typed text, resolve to a host entry in this order:
  1. Exact hostname match (case-insensitive)
  2. Unique prefix match (if exactly one hostname starts with the typed text)
  3. Exact IP/host field match
  4. Literal fallback — create a dummy entry with hostname=host=typed text (passed raw to ssh)

  ---
  SSH Command Construction

  ssh [-v] [-o legacy options] [-J jumpuser@jumphost] [-p port] [user@]target

  - user = per-host user, else global ssh_user, else omitted
  - jumphost = per-host jumphost, else global jumpserver if global_jumphost=yes, else omitted
  - Jump is omitted entirely when /o flag is active
  - target = entry.host if set, else entry.hostname
  - Legacy options only added when /l flag or entry.legacy=true

  ---
  Connection Flow

  1. Parse CLI args
  2. Load config and hosts
  3. Render TUI (visible slice only if scrolling needed)
  4. Get target: from CLI arg or interactive prompt
  5. Resolve to a HostEntry
  6. Merge per-host legacy flag into command flags
  7. Build and display the ssh command
  8. If dry-run: print and exit
  9. Otherwise: exec ssh ... via subprocess.call(); propagate exit code
  10. Handle ssh not found in PATH (exit 127)

  ---
  Graceful Degradation

  - No rich: plain text host list, no colors, no table
  - No prompt_toolkit: plain input(), no fuzzy complete, no history, no slash-command activation
  - Both deps are optional; the tool is usable with neither

  ---
  File Locations Summary

  ┌─────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  File   │                 Default path                 │
  ├─────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Config  │ ./config.ini or ~/.config/sshmngr/config.ini │
  ├─────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Hosts   │ ./hosts.csv or ~/.config/sshmngr/hosts.csv   │
  ├─────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ History │ ~/.config/sshmngr/.history                   │
  └─────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  ($XDG_CONFIG_HOME overrides ~/.config if set)

  ---
  Exit Codes

  - 0 — success or dry-run
  - 1 — no host provided
  - 127 — ssh not found in PATH
  - 130 — interrupted (Ctrl+C)
  - Any other — forwarded from ssh itself
